The beak is blackish with a noticeable egg tooth, which disappeared on the 18th-33rd day. When born, the eyes of the black american swift chicks are closed, they slightly open them on the 7th-8th day and fully open on the 14th-16th day[ 20]. On the 6-7th day, fluff appears on the head, back and upper chest, by 13-14 days the chicks are almost completely covered with dark gray fluff. The color of the fluff is darker than in the chicks of the genus Streptoprocne, but lighter than in other representatives of the genus Cypseloides. During the first two weeks, the chicks are not capable of thermoregulation and are very dependent on their parents.